" Gone with the wind ": film legend Olivia de Havilland is dead
Film legend and Oscar winner Olivia de Havilland is dead.
She died of natural causes in Paris on Sunday at the age of 104, confirmed her spokeswoman for the German Press Agency.
De Havilland was known for her role as Melanie Hamilton in the Southern epic " Gone with the Wind " (1939).
Born in Tokyo to British parents, Olivia de Havilland moved to California as an infant.
The Austrian theater man Max Reinhardt discovered the 19-year-old in the role of Hermia in Shakespeare's " Midsummer Night's Dream. "
The Warner Brothers film studio signed her for seven years and brought her to prominence alongside Eroll Flynn.
She made eight films with the heartbreaker.
In 1946 she won her first Oscar in the leading role of " To Each His Own. "
The film was shown in Germany under the title " Mutterherz. "
Three years later she received the award for best actress in William Wyler's " The Heiress. "
She also received a lot of recognition as a neurotic eccentric in " Der dunkle Spiegel " and " Die Schlangengrube. "
Daphne du Maurier suggested her in 1952 for the leading role in the film adaptation of her novel " My Cousin Rachel. "
The play was a worldwide success.
She played in " Lullaby for a Corpse " with her long-time friend Bette Davis.
His marriage to the writer Marcus Goodrich (1946 to 1953) produced his son Benjamin.
In Paris, de Havilland married the journalist Pierre Paul Galante and had his daughter Gisèle with him.
This marriage also broke up.
Rumors of an affair with former British Prime Minister Edward Heath have never been confirmed.
