Heil wants to examine other sectors after the meat industry
The COVID-19 crisis brought the situation in parts of the meat industry to light once again.
Tightening of laws is imminent.
But are they right - and will they remain so?
Following the now planned strict regulations against abuses in the meat industry, Federal Minister of Labour Hubertus Heil (SPD) wants to examine other sectors as well.
" We will look at industry by industry and then take appropriate measures for the respective industry if necessary, " Heil told the German Press Agency in Berlin.
Germany's employers are already warning against restricting work contracts in general.
Following the mass outbreak of corona at meat giant Tönnies in North Rhine-Westphalia, the Federal Cabinet wants to pass a law by Heil this Wednesday.
Large-scale slaughterhouses should no longer be allowed to employ external personnel for slaughter, cutting and meat processing.
To this end, the use of contract and temporary workers is to be banned there.
Employer President Ingo Kramer told dpa: " Stay away from a general restriction on work contracts and temporary employment if you do not want to strangle the economy completely. "
Contracts for work and services are, for example, the essential basis for creating added value for customers in a wide range of trades, the construction industry and plant engineering.
" The mistakes of individuals cannot destroy such an important instrument. "
Heil assured: " My aim is not to ban contracts for work and services everywhere in the German economy. "
Contracts for work and services make sense.
" If an industrial company commissions a tradesman to install a security system, this is a completely normal work contract. "
The German meat industry considers a ban on work contracts and temporary agency work to be unconstitutional in its sector alone.
According to a statement on the proposed law, the " Neue Osnabrücker Zeitung " (Saturday) reports that it is not possible to explain why different labour laws should apply to the portioning and packaging of cheese in the future than to sausages.
In the event of a ban, the consumer price would rise by 10 to 20 percent per kilo and product.
According to the results of an audit by the North Rhine-Westphalia Occupational Safety and Health Administration, many Eastern European employees from contractors worked in the sector, sometimes 16 hours a day.
They often had no rest.
Wages were withheld for protective equipment or rent.
It was also noted that the situation regarding the accommodation of employees was often miserable.
Heil said that a relatively strict law for the meat industry had already come into force in 2017.
However, these have been circumvented by " tricky constructions. "
" A fundamental clean-up is now required. "
The politician announced: " The Occupational Safety and Health Act, which we want to pass in the Cabinet at the end of July, also includes measures that not only affect the meat industry - for example, higher examination rates for occupational safety and health or clear criteria for communal accommodation. "
The draft presented to dpa includes amendments to the Act on the Protection of Workers' Rights in the Meat Industry and the Occupational Health and Safety Act.
Brandenburg's consumer protection minister, Ursula Nonnemacher (Green Party), believes that more intensive controls are necessary.
" I would like us to be able to carry out even more checks in many supervisory areas: food inspections, animal welfare, everything possible, including animal transport, for example, " said Nonnemacher on Sunday in the RBB programme " Brandenburg aktuell. "
However, more personnel positions are also needed for more checks.
