Baden-Württemberg: Over 250 illegal car races recorded
Stuttgart - Despite all the threatened penalties and court rulings, drivers continue to step on the gas in countless illegal races on the roads of Baden-Württemberg: In the past year and the first four months of this year, the police in the south-west have already registered more than 250 illegal car races.
There are no comparable figures for previous years, but the speeders are increasingly making work for the judicial authorities: A total of 155 investigations into illegal races were conducted at the public prosecutor's offices between Konstanz and Mannheim in 2018, a year later there were already 252 and in the current year by the beginning of June 151.
The races were less about organised events, as can be seen from the response of the Ministry of the Interior to an inquiry by the Landtag-SPD.
In most cases, the drivers competed against each other spontaneously or fled from the police - this is also reported as an illegal race.
The drivers were mainly German men between the ages of 18 and 60.
113 fines - 15 times imprisonment
Only in comparatively few cases are speeders caught and asked to pay: According to the Ministry of the Interior, a total of 113 fines have been imposed and 15 prison sentences handed down since 2018.
However, there are no indications that the number of illegal car races is actually increasing.
On the contrary, other drivers reacted more sensitively than in the past due to the numerous tragic accidents and lawsuits, and reported more frequently, said a ministry spokesman.
Autobahn 8 is particularly popular with racers. Again and again, drivers brake the traffic there in order to make room for themselves and use the free track for a race.
Last August, a dozen drivers were caught near Kirchheim unter Teck; three months earlier, there were as many as 18 drivers on the A8 near Merklingen.
The A81 is the most popular " race track "
The police even register more races on the A81 than on any other federal motorway.
With a speed limit, an attempt is being made to slow down the speeders on the particularly affected section between Engen and Geisingen.
The mostly high-priced and pimped-up sports and luxury cars often have Swiss license plates because drivers resort to racing in Germany because of the high penalties for driving too fast and car racing in the neighbouring country.
For the SPD, the speed limit must not be reduced to a few routes: " With a general speed limit of 130 kilometres per hour, we would get rid of this problem on motorways, " says Martin Rivoir, the traffic expert for the SPD parliamentary group.
" The inhibition threshold for speeders would be significantly higher if you were not allowed to travel legally here and there at 200 kilometres per hour or more. "
Rivoir thinks less of education or image campaigns: " Anyone who ignores all the rules in this way and puts not only their own lives, but also the lives of other road users at risk, can hardly be reached with reason. "
ADAC calls for stronger police crackdown
However, this is not enough for the ADAC: " We assume that racers will not be deterred by the speed limits, " says Holger Bach, Head of Transport and Environment at ADAC Württemberg.
He is calling for additional and tougher checks on the affected routes.
Not infrequently, the high-speed trial of strength turns into painful and momentous seriousness: Since January 2019 and until April 2020, three people across the country have died in the races, two of them innocent bystanders in a night-time crash in the centre of Stuttgart and one in Gerlingen.
Two young men are said to have competed in a car race there in November.
One of the vehicles came off the road, crashed into a garden wall and stopped on its side, and the 18-year-old co-driver died.
21 other people have been injured in the races over the past two years.
However, in the opinion of Minister of the Interior Thomas Strobl, stricter penalties are not necessary: " There is no need for legislative action to sanction illegal motor vehicle races more severely, " says the paper of the Ministry of the Interior.
