Ex-Dortmunder Immobile mit Dreierpack für Lazio Rom
Ciro Immobile is now on a par with Bavaria's Robert Lewandowski in the race for Europe's Golden Boot.
Former Dortmund player Ciro Immobile still has the best chance of becoming the top scorer in the Italian football championship.
The former BVB pro contributed three goals to the 5: 1 (1: 1) victory of Lazio Rome at Hellas Verona, including two converted penalties in the aftermath of both halves.
This means that the 30-year-old, who came fourth in the standings two games before the end of the season, now has 34 goals for the season on his account - just as many were scored by Robert Lewandowski of FC Bayern Munich in the last Bundesliga season.
In Italy, Cristiano Ronaldo has scored 30 goals so far, while the Portuguese superstar faced Sampdoria Genoa with the leader in the evening.
Fleetwood Mac co-founder Peter Green has died
His life was like a rollercoaster ride: After a rapid ascent with Fleetwood Mac, it went steeply downhill and then slowly uphill again.
Now blues rock guitarist Peter Green has passed away at the age of 73.
Ingenious guitarist, drug junkie, cult fan: The co-founder of the band Fleetwood Mac, Peter Green, is dead.
He died peacefully in his sleep at the age of 73, family members announced in an official statement on Saturday that a further statement would be announced for the next few days.
Top musicians such as Peter Frampton praised Green as one of the best blues and rock guitarists.
In an emotional reaction, Mick Fleetwood spoke of a " monumental loss " for all former and current members of the band Fleetwood Mac.
Drummer Fleetwood and guitarist Green founded the now legendary band in London in 1967, and his dreamy instrumental hit " Albatross " remains unforgotten to this day.
The musician's life (" The End Of The Game, " " In The Skies ") resembled a rollercoaster ride.
With Fleetwood Mac, Green experienced a rapid rise - but the band celebrated their greatest successes without him.
There is said to have been a dispute, among other things, because Green wanted to donate all of the group's profits to charity.
He began to perform in wide robes and with a large crucifix.
Psychological problems are also said to have played a role.
Just three years after their founding, Green left the band in 1970.
This was followed by a social decline.
The blues rock guitarist suffered from drug abuse and schizophrenia, as biographers reported.
Green was treated in psychiatry for a long time.
During most of the 1970s, the musician disappeared from the scene.
He is said to have lived temporarily on the street, worked as a cemetery gardener and spent some time in an Israeli kibbutz.
Green was born in 1946 to a Jewish working-class family in the London district of Bethnal Green.
Even at a young age he was enthusiastic about US blues musicians such as B.B. King and Muddy Waters.
He learned his first guitar chords at the age of eleven.
At the age of 15, the teenager began to play the guitar professionally and five years later got the chance to appear on stage as lead guitarist for the instrumental band Peter B's Looners.
A little later he was engaged by the Bluesbreakers to replace his idol Eric Clapton.
In the midst of the blues boom, Green founded Fleetwood Mac in the summer of 1967 together with his Bluesbreakers colleagues Mick Fleetwood and John McVie.
The song " Albatross, " composed by Green, brought the group their first number one hit in the winter of 1968 / 69 and catapulted them to the top of the British music scene.
But the rapid ascent soon showed its downsides: Green could not cope with the media hype, his experiments with the drug LSD became more and more extreme.
He later commented on life between music and addiction in an interview: " The worst thing that happened to me in my life was drugs - the best thing was to land a number one hit. "
Towards the end of the decade, Green achieved a surprising success in 1979 with an album inspired by religious themes.
Meanwhile, Fleetwood Mac swam without him in a new formation on a wave of success.
Their 1977 album " Rumours " sold more than 40 million copies worldwide.
Despite various small solo successes, Green did not make a major comeback until he started again in 1996 with a group of musician friends.
At the time, the British " Daily Telegraph " spoke of a rock star returning to earth.
Free of drugs, Green released several albums with the Peter Green Splinter Group until the band broke up in 2004.
For music experts, he was already a blues legend during his lifetime - and with his gentle sound he was one of the most influential guitarists of the past decades.
